and decays to zero as a third order inverse power law. 















Up to now, we considered general PPPs for the distribution of BSs in each tier. One simplifying assumption in the literature is to assume that PPPs determining the locations of BSs are homogenous. In this case, $\mu_k(t)$ for all tiers is given by $\mu_k(t) = 2\pi t \ensuremath{\mathsf{1}_{\left\{{t \geq 0}\right\}}}$, where $\ensuremath{\mathsf{1}_{\left\{{\cdot}\right\}}}$ is the indicator function.  Using this expression for $\mu_k(t)$ in Theorem \ref{Theorem 1}, we obtain the following approximation result for the distribution of AWI when all BSs are homogeneously distributed over the plane according to a PPP with differing BS intensity parameters $\lambda_k$ from tier to tier.   

\begin{thm} \label{Theorem 2} 
Assume that $\Phi_{\Lambda^{(k)}} $ is a homogeneous PPP with a mean measure given $\Lambda^{(k)}\left({\mathcal{A}}\right)  = \lambda_k \cdot \mbox{area}\left({\mathcal{A}}\right)$. Then, for all $x \in {\ensuremath{{\ensuremath{\mathbb{{R}}}}}}$,
\begin{eqnarray}
\left| {\ensuremath{\mathsf{Pr}\left\{{\frac{I_{{\ensuremath{\boldsymbol{{\lambda}}}}} - \ensuremath{\mathsf{E}\left[{I_{{\ensuremath{\boldsymbol{{\lambda}}}}}} \right]}}{\sqrt{\ensuremath{\mathsf{Var}\left({I_{{\ensuremath{\boldsymbol{{\lambda}}}}}} \right)}} } \le x}\right\}} - \Psi(x)}\right| \leq \Xi \cdot c(x),
\end{eqnarray}
where $\Xi = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}} \sum_{k=1}^K \frac{\lambda_k P_k^3 m_{H^3}^{(k)} \int_0^\infty G_k^3(t) t dt}{\left({\sum_{k=1}^K \lambda_k P_k^2 m_{H^2}^{(k)} \int_0^\infty G_k^2(t) t dt}\right)^\frac32}$, $c(x) = \min\left({0.4785, \frac{31.935}{1+\left| {x}\right|^3}}\right)$ and $\Psi(x) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}\int_{-\infty}^x {\ensuremath{{\rm e}^{{- \frac{t^2}{2}}}}} dt$, which is the standard normal CDF.    
\end{thm}
\begin{IEEEproof}
The proof follows from Theorem \ref{Theorem 1} by replacing $\mu_k(t)$ with $2\pi t \ensuremath{\mathsf{1}_{\left\{{t \geq 0}\right\}}}$.
\end{IEEEproof}


























